column168: Narrative:  On 4-01-05 @ 1215 hours, a tank car/HAZMAT loader was beginning a transfer of MDI for Dow Chemical. In order to start the transfer the pressure has to be relieved from the trailer. When he opened the valve to release the pressure from the trailer, a mist of product came out of the release pipe that is elevated approx. 5 ft. and the wind blew it onto the front of the trailer and onto the back of the truck sleeper and the truck fenders. No product got on any individual. During the previous transfer the nitrogen tank that was used to blow the product line clean was empty and the air from the railcar was used to blow the line clean. The nitrogen tank gauge read that there was still pressure inside the tank.  When blowing product line clean, the valve on the platform side of air fitting was open allowing some product to enter the airline.  This valve is open when using nitrogen.
column169: Root Cause(s):    1. Vendor’s gauge on the nitrogen tank failed on the previous transfer.  The tank read 320 lbs pressure when the tank was actually empty. (delivers @ 325 lbs)  a. Needing to clear the product line we used the air pressure from the railcar though we did not have the proper fittings.    b. The employee was not familiar with using air pressure from the railcar to clear the product line.    Corrective Action(s):    1. Communicate back to the nitrogen vendor the gauge failing to notify us of the tank being empty and what measures can be taken to prevent another gauge failure.  2. Compressed nitrogen stored as a back-up source. (verify with shipper)  3. Add additional pressure gauge to system on our side coming off the nitrogen bottle to determine the nitrogen tank level.  4. Evaluate the need for a dry air system.

Unit was EB on SR 146.  Unit entered a left curving grade, driver dropped off right sholder of road.  Vehicle rolled onto it's right side, went off the roadway, continued rolling back onto it's wheels, then rolled back onto it's left side.  When units came to rest, manholes of compartments 1 and 2 were leaking. Spill pads were immediately placed by where leaks occurred.  County road department was at scene and put down sand to contain spillage.  Holes were drilled in side of tanker and product was pumped off and delivered.  150 gallons of foam/diesel mixture was vaccumed up and 110 tons of contaminated soil was removed (8 or 9 truckloads).  We have not received bills for product lost, property damage or remediation. When we get this information, it will be forwarded to your agency.  Authorities contacted:  OH EPA, NRC, A1 towing, Fire Departments, BBU Services, Protera, Insurance companies, County Road Department.

column168: Product was being transferred into the customer's storage tank. While the product was being transferred, an elbow in the discharge pipe on top of the cargo tank began to leak. The transfer was terminated and air pressure was released from the cargo tank. The elbow was removed and replaced and the remainder of the product was transferred. Oil dry was placed around the cargo tank to contain the product and water that was used to neutralize the product. This was cleaned up by plant personnel for proper disposal.    The leak was a result of the rubber lining of the elbow having deteriorated to the point where the product began to contact the metal of the elbow. The corrosive nature of the product eventually caused a small hole to develop in the elbow.
column169: The elbow was replaced with one having a different material for the lining. Inspection frequency of the discharge piping will be made on a 90 day cycle.

THEN I GOT EMERGENCY CLEANUP KIT.  I PUT DOWN ABSORBANTS AS FAST AS I COULD.  I CALLED PERS, DEP, COUNTY, AND OFFICE TO REPORT.  IMMEDIATE RESPONSE BY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND POLICE WERE THERE.  THEY SAID I HAD EVERYTHING UNDER CONTROL AND THEY NEED NO REPORT AND LEFT.  DEP CALLED ME BACK AND TOLD ME TO EXAVATE TEH SPILLED SOIL AND DISPOSE OF IT PROPERLY.  WE DID THIS AT THAT TIME.  ALL SOIL WAS TAKEN TO LANDFILL.

column168: Cargo from British Airways flight 203/16 Aprilwas offloaded from the aircraft & transported by truck to British Airways' cargo terminal.  As the cargo unit load devices were being emptied, packages were removed and placed on wooden skids for storage. The subject package toppled over onto its side as it was being placed, by hand, onto a wooden skid.  At this point, fumes were emitting from the box and the fiberboard box was getting wet from the contents leaking from inside.  The cargo warehouse was then evacuated & CHEMTREC was called.  CHEMTREC evaluated the HAZMAT information and advised that it was safe to return to the facility and carry out a self clean-up.  Approximately .3 liters leaked from the inner package. Most of this was absorbed by the packaging material & the remainder was soaked up by the fiberboard box itself.  T  The carto was opened & the inner package lid was resealed.  Fumes were extracted from the facility by the ventilation system & then subsided.

Pumper off loading tankcar of Styrene Monomer (CGTX-26293) to storage tank T-271.  Pumper filled storage tank with targeted amount and reset meter to continue to off   load to T-272. Pumper failed to switch the control to T-272 and continued to fill  tank T-271.  Tank 271 high level interlock failed to operate as designed and that resulted in the overfilling the tank, causing the release of 300 pounds of material within the dike area.
column169: 1.) Tie DeltaV control alarms to sound in the east yard area in addition to the present high level alarm system.    2.)Run fill checlks on all staorage tanks for better probe calibration.     3.) Look for other types of probes that may hold calibration better.

column169: The driver was filling the UG gasoline tank. He momentairly went into the cab and the tank overfilled. As soon as he noticed it, he imediately closed the valve. He called the fire dept. He then took absorbent booms and pads and placed them to contain the product. He received help from employees from a truck repair shop next door and our employees. They also placed "Oil Dry" to absorb the product. The absorbant materials were all placed into drums. These will be properly disposed of. They were able to complete the containment and pick up in approximately 1 hour. The MN Duty Officer was called. They inturn notified the MPCA & the DOT. The driver was told that he must follow company procedures of measuring the amount of product before filling and must always be in attendance of the fill hose during delivery. Also the nozzle has been replaced with a "tight fill" type to prevent any further spills.

column168: Driver exited off Interstate 80 east at Golconda, NV, onto Highway 789 north, that had a posted speed of 55mph. After about 2 miles he came upon a left curve with a  posted speed of 25 mph. Driver estimates speed into curve at 35-40 mph. Vehicle rolled onto right side.Peroxide leaked out of top onto ground and ignited some brush.  Local emergency response put out fire. Was very localized and small. Was determined that cargo tank barrel was ripped. No way to remove lading due to cargo tank position on side of roadway. With permission of Nevada authorities on site, and advice of shipper, lading released into surrounding dirt area off roadway. Peroxide will decompose from chemical formula H202 to H20 or water in time. Site was secured with 24 hour guard service to prevent human contact during decomposition time.  Site was prepared prior to release to prevent organic matter ignition. Highway 789 was closed to traffic for over 24 hours.
column169: Driver entered curve too fast. As of the submission of this report we don't have Police Report nor adjuster report with photos and diagrams to make further recommendations.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, SURFACE CONTAMINATED OBJECTS (SCO-I OR SCO-II) NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: On April 12, 2005 at approximately 1430 hours a truck arrived at the Duratek, Inc. Memphis facility from Forward Air - Memphis with three radioactive containers of GE Nuclear equipment and three non-radioactive packages, all from Taiwan.  The three radioactive packages were labeled as Yellow III's with T.I.'s of 1.8, 2.0 and 6.4.  The truck did not have placards as required by DOT.  There were no shipping papers with the load indicating there was radioactive material being transported.  The dose rate in the cab of the truck was 2.8 mR/Hr.  The Tennessee Department of Radiological Health was notified and Duratek, Inc. Memphis obtained permission to accept the load and off-load the containers.  The containers were off-loaded and the highest 1-meter reading was 6 mR/Hr.    The trucking company (Accelerated, Inc.) does not have a Hazmat Registration and the driver was not qualified to haul Hazardous Material.  The driver stated that the load was picked up at 1215 hours and he had made two other stops before arriving at the Duratek, Inc. Memphis facility.    Menlo Worldwide was contracted by GE Nuclear to get the packages through Customs and forwarded on to the Duratek, Inc. Memphis facility.
column169: GE Nuclear is going to make all transportation arrangements from the air forwarding companies to the Duratek, Inc. Memphis facility from now on.  This will insure that the trucking company is qualified to haul the material and that they have the appropriate shipping papers with the load.
column172: General packaging, for type A radioactive materials

column162: MANAGER, DANGEROUS GOODS, SAFETY AND REGULATORY
column168: Continental Airlines (CO) transported 11 boxes containing paint, 1 of which sustained damage. Notification was made by ramp personnel that one piece had leaked in bin 5.     The damage is thought to have occurred once the bin was open because the paint was still wet and surrounding passenger bags were reported to be damaged.      The box had a triangular hole approximately 1 1/2 to 2 inch size on the bottom of box which damaged the inner package containing the paint.     The box appeared to be very sturdy construction consisting of two layers of corrugated cardboard and a corrugated cardboard liner.     CO maintenance cleaned and inspected the bin concluded that the paint spill was isolated only on the floor of bin 5 and did not leak through adjacent seams.
column169: CO will recommend that Shipper ultilize Specification packaging for subsequent shipments. CO feels that shipper choice of packaging is inferior.

column169: Conversation with the original shipper has revealed that product packaging changes will be implemented by the end of May 2005. Proper handling of this product was discussed with all necessary employees for handling of future shipments.

column168: The brakes failed when the driver attempted to stop at a red light. Driver swerved to miss a vehicle and overturned. There was no release of hazardous material but there was an evacuation and road closure for two hours approximately in order to upright the truck.
column169: The company is having the brakes inspected and has a rollover prevention policy titled, "SLIP OFF STAY OFF" with cab posters and training reminders.  The idea is to bring the vehicle under control without attempting to radically change the path which can cause liquid load shifting and add to the potential for overturn. After each such accident a committee reviews the investigative facts to determine whether the driver followed company safety practices and whether disciplinary actions are appropriate.     Our employees receive recurrent training for defensive driving, proper backing techniques and how to prevent rollovers. Employees must pass a driver recertification test every three years.

column168: Driver had finished unloading from rail car to trailer and was commencing disconnection procedures when he noticed that it was taking longer than normal.  He blew down the lines three times in total to ensure there was no residual liquid in the lines.  Upon breaking the connection with the “B” side valve, driver noticed a slight vapor cloud emanate from the port.  He replaced the plug in the valve and confirmed there was no leaking from around it.  Driver applied lubricant to the valve’s stem and worked the valve a few times to get it to seal.  Driver contacted corporate office and was instructed to mark the valve “do not use”.  Rail car was emptied and depressurized, then repaired.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Less than 1 pound of vapor was estimated to have been released.

Driver noticed slight buildup of pressure behind plug in vapor valve as he began hooking up hoses to unload the rail car.  He connected up, confirmed there were no leaks and commenced emptying the rail car.  Upon emptying the rail car, he blew down, disconnected the hoses, and removed the pipe adapter.  Driver ascertained the vapor valve was still leaking by minutely.  Driver replaced the plug to temporarily contain the leak and contacted the corporate office.  Driver was instructed to slightly move the handle of the ball valve to see if he could get leak to stop.  This handle adjustment stopped the leak.  Rail car was degassed and brought into a vacuum for repair.  No evacuations were made, no injuries reported, and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.  Less than 1 pound of vapor was estimated to have been released.

Driver arrived at customer location and noticed product had spilled in the back of the trailer..  Valve/Cap on Portafeed was not properly closed.  The cap was not properly secured allowing a release of product into trailer.  A cleanup company was called to the scene to conduct a cleanup.

RESPONDER WAS CALLED TO LEAKING PACKAGE ON PD-3 HIGH VOLUME PICK OFF.  RESPONDED WITH PPE (GOGGLE, BOOTS APRON, GLOVES), TOOK SPILL CAR TO AREA AND CORDONED OFF THE AREA.  LEAKING PACKAGE WAS A USED PRODUCE BOX WITH NO MARKINGS IDENTIFYING THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE WE DISCOVERED VARIOUS HOUSEHOLD CHEMICALS, INCLUDING BLEACH, WINDEX, RUBBING ALCOHOL, AND AEROSOL CANS; ALONG WITH ADDITIONAL NON-HAZADOUS HOUSEHOLD ITMES.  THERE WERE NO MAKRINGS ON THE BOX TO INDICATE THAT IT CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  HAZARDOUS ITEMS WERE DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE FACILITY DMP, NON-HAZARDOUS ITEMS WERE FORWARDED TO THE SONSIGNEE.

column168: A 55-gallon drum was being transferred when the forklift blade punctured the side.  The drum was laid on its side to prevent further spillage.  The drum was overpacked, the spill cleaned, and all were prepared for proper disposition.

4/4/05, 5:00PM: WHILE WORKING IN OAK ISLAND YARD, NEWARK, NJ, THE ENGINEER ON YPOI31 NOTED TANK CAR GATX 17082 (NON-INSULATED), LOAD, N-PROPYL ACETATE, LOCATED ON TRACK RUNNING #3 WHILE IN RECENTLY ARRIVED CSXT TRAIN Q300, LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  LEAK WAS REPORTED TO TRAINMASTER, WHO IN TURN CONTACTED CR S.T.O. WITH CONFERENCE CALL TO CONRAIL'S A. RICHTER, MGR., RISK MANAGEMENT.  YARD PERSONNEL HAD PLACED A BUCKET UNDERNEATH THE CAR, BUT MOST OF THE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TOP WAS EVAPORATING BEFORE FALLING INTO THE BUCKET.  SHIPPER CONTACTED VIA 24-HOUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TELEPHONE NUMBER (CHEMTREC) AND AFTER RECEIVING INFORMATION, CONTRACTED WITH REACT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TO INSPECT AND AFFECT REPAIRS AND/OR SECUREMENT OF CAR.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY REACT AND CR NOTED 4 OF 4 LIQUID VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE SECUREMENT NUTS NOT EVEN HAND TIGHT.  THE TANK CAR WAS VENTED DOWN TO 0 P.S.I. THROUGH THE AIR VALVE, CEASING THE LEAK.  SECUREMENT NUTS SECURED TOOL TIGHT AND ALL OTHER FITTINGS INSPECTED WITH NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS.  CAR OKAYED FOR FOWARDING TO ORIGINAL DESTINATION (SCHEDULED FOR DELIVERY 4/5/05).  AT TIME OF INSPECTION, TANK CAR'S OUTAGE WAS MEASURED THROUGH THE MIDLAND MAGNETIC GAUGING DEVICE, AND FOUND TO BE 4" (MEASURED AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00PM).
column169: AT TIME OF INITIAL INSPECTION BY REACT, BREADBOX (WHERE LIQUID VALVE WAS LOCATED) SEAL # "HCH MARKETING 1566" WAS INTACT AND REMOVED FOR INSPECTION, REPLACED AT TERMINATION OF INCIDENT BY REACT SEAL "00080".  NO SEAL WAS PRESENT ON THE MANWAY COVER AT TIME OF INSPECTION, HOWEVER, CONTRACTOR APPLIED REACT SEAL "000071".  WITH THE PRESENCE OF THE INTACT SHIPPER'S SEAL ON THE BREAD BOX, IT APPEARED THAT TRAINING, INSPECTION, AND PREPARATION FOR TRANSPORTATION PROCEDURES ARE NOT ADEQUATE, NOR DOT-COMPLIANT, AT THE SHIPPING LOCATION.

While driver was loading the truck, the dock plate slipped off causing the forklift to roll forward. The driver was unable to stop the forklift before it made contact with a 55 gallon steel drum. The drum was punctured towards the bottom of the drum by one of the forks causing a 4 inch hole in the drum.  The driver immediately put absorbent down to absorb the liquid. The drum was placed in a salvage drum and all spilled material was cleaned up. The clean up material was placed in two 55 gallon metal drums for disposal. The transporter obtained Emergency EPA # and profiled out for roper disposal. National response was contacted.

column168: DRIVER EXITED INTERSTATE 10 WESTBOUND AT EXIT 583 ONTO US-90 WESTBOUND. UPON REACHING NORTH FOSTER ROAD, DRIVER MADE LEFT HAND TURN. DRIVER STATED THAT HE MADE THE TURN TO SHARP AND FELT THE TANK SHIFT TO THE RIGHT SIDE CAUSING THE TANKER TO ROLLOVER ONTO THE PASSENGER SIDE. THE IMPACT CAUSED A SMALL CRACK ON THE REAR SEAM OF THE TANKER HALFWAY UP ON THE PASSENGER SIDE. APPROXIMATELY 700 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS RELEASED. IMPACT AREAS ASPHALT ROAD SURFACE AND SOIL. NO WATER SOURCES AFFECTED.  SAN ANTONIO FIRE DEPARTMENT (SAFD) RESPONDED AND DIKED OFF THE TAIL END OF THE TANKER AND THE AREA FUEL WAS FLOWING. SAFD PERFORMED A COLD-TAP OF THE TANKER AND ALL REMAINING FUEL WAS REMOVED. TRACTOR AND TANKER WERE UP-RIGHTED AND TOWED OFF THE SITE.  AREA OF IMPACT ARE AS FOLLOWS: FUEL TRAIL FROM TANKER TO THE SOUTH SIDE OF NORTH FOSTER ROAD, 40 FEET LONG BY 20 FEET IN WIDTH. IMPACTED SOIL ON SOUTH SHOULDER OF NORTH FOSTER ROAD 23 FEET LONG BY 3 FEET IN WIDTH BY 1 FOOT IN DEPTH. THE ASPHALT ROAD SURFACE WAS MECHANICALLY REMEDIATED. THE IMPACTED SOIL AREA WAS EXCAVATED. CONFIRMATION SOIL SAMPLES INDICATED THAT THE AREA WAS WITHIN ACCEPTABLE ACTION LEVELS PER STATE OF TEXAS REGULATIONS.  SEE ATTACHED FOR PHOTOGRAPHS.
column169: ALL COMPANY DRIVERS HAVE BEEN REFRESHED IN PROPER SPEED CONTROL WHILE EXITING HIGHWAY OFF RAMPS. Upon bringing the tanker into the cleaning bay there was a release of free product while attempting to remove the internal valve for cleaning, due to the external valve not being shut off.  One employee was exposed to the release and taken to the Wetzel County Hospital where he was treated and released.  Terminal personnel performed the cleanup using neutralizer.  The cleanup materials were placed into a fifty-five gallon recovery drum and will be held at the facility awaiting disposition.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and was due to the external valve being left open, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

column168: DURING THE COURSE OF NORMAL MECHANICAL INSPECTION OF TANK CAR PPGX 1891, THE CARRIER'S EMPLOYEE DETECTED AN ODOR OF CHLORINE IN THE AREA NEAR THE SUBJECT CAR.  THE CARRIER'S EMPLOYEE NOTIFIED THE YEARD SUPERVISOR AND THE AREA AROUND THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE PROPER AUTHORITIES NOTIFIED. THE CARRIER NOTIFIED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENT (MDE), AND THE SHIPPER OF THE INCIDENT. A TEAM CONSISTING OF PERSONNEL FROM THE CARRIER'S CONTRACTOR AND MDE INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT CHLORINE VAPOR WAS ESCAPING FROM THE RIGHT SIDE VAPOR VALVE.  THE VALVE HANDLE WAS TIGHT, BUT VAPOR WAS STILL ESCAPING AROUND FROM THE VALVE OUTLET.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VAPOR VALVE OUTLET PPLUG WA LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT AND NOT FULLY SEATED IN THE VALVE.  THE OUTLET VALVE PLUG WAS THEN TIGHTENED AND THE VAPOR RELEASE CEASED.  THE VALVE BODY AND VALVE OUTLET WERE THEN CHECKED FOR LEAKS. FINDING NO OTHER LEAKAGE, THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO THE COSIGNEE.  THE CONSIGNEE(CAR OWNER) WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM WITH THE RIGHT SIDE VAPOR VALVE AND WAS REQUESTED TO INSPECT/REPAIR THE VALVE AS NECESSARY TO ENSURE THAT IT CLOSED AND SEALED PROPERLY. column168: BNSF INTERMODAL HUB PERSONNEL REPORTED PRODUCT STAIN ON AN INTERMODAL FLATCAR THAT ARRIVED ON AN INBOUND TRAIN.  THE STAIN WAS UNDER THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OF TANK CONTAINER PDQU 200408.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ON PDQU 200408 IN THE CLOSED POSITION, BUT A SMALL PRODUCT DRIP EMANATING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP (BOC).  RESPONDERS REMOVED AND CLEANED THE BOC.  THE BOC GASKET WAS INSPECTED AND IT HAD A SMALL GOUGE WHICH ALLOWED TRAPPED PRODUCT BETWEEN THE CLOSED INTERNAL VALVE AND THE BOC TO ESCAPE.  WHEN THIS TANK CONTAINER WAS BOTTOM LOADED VIA THIS VALVE, A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IS USUALLY TRAPPED BETWEEN THE CLOSED INTERNAL VALVE AND THE BOC.  THIS TRAPPED PRODUCT IS WHAT LEAKED.  THE DAMAGED BOC GASKET WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW GASKET AND THE BOC WAS TIGHTENED, ENDING FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE BY 1745 HRS. CDT, 4/06.  THE SMALL 6 INCH DIAMETER STAIN ON THE INTERMODAL FLATCAR WAS WIPED CLEAN.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER'S PRE-TRIP INSPECTION PROCESS IS FULLY IMPLEMENTED AND VALIDATED AS IT RELATES TO THE MECHANICAL FITNESS AND SECUREMENT OF ALL VALVES AND FITTINGS, INCLUDING GASKETS.

column168: Driver was making a delivery to customer and during the unloading process noticed that the IBC was seeping material from a seam.  All material was contained within the box truck.  Response included absorbing the spilled material that was on the trailer floor and transferring remaining product from the leaking IBC into another container via transfer pump.
column169: Ulrich has instructed employees to be more vigilant in inspecting the exterior of the IBC's before filling or offering for transportation.  However, the crack in the IBC was almost invisible to the naked eye.  Upon return, the IBC was pressure tested and soap applied to find the pin hole leak.  The IBC has been triple rinsed and destroyed.

column168: Cargo tank pre-loaded for delivery the next day.  The morning after cargo tank was pre-loaded, employee notice a vapor cloud around the cargo tank and he then called his supervisor.  It was determined that product was leaking from a hole in the side of the vessel.  Fire Department was immediately notified, they responded and isolated area.  Company personnel transferred product from leaking cargo tank to another cargo tank.  Leak stopped within five minutes from the start of product transfer.  Environmental response contracted was called in for cleanup and disposal of spilled material.  Duration of release was possibly 2 to 3 hours.    Leaking cargo tank was subsequently taken out of service, cleaned and sent in to Bulk Transportation shop for repairs.  We discovered that the Durkane lining on the cargo tank cracked, allowing the acid to contact the mild steel vessel resulting corrosion and failure.
column169: Degradation of cargo tank lining accelerated due frequent washouts, which were required for various products being transported.  The recommended preventative action is to dedicate cargo tank to one or two types of products, therefore reducing the need for frequent washouts.

column42: AMMONIA SOLUTION, RELATIVE DENSITY BETWEEN 0.880 AND 0.957 AT 15 DEGREES C IN WATER, WITH MORE THAN 10 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 35 PERCENT AMMONIA
column168: At approximately 5:30pm on 4/29/05 the driver was at the remote delivery site unloaded. The driver had already unloaded the pull unit into the customers tank and was in the process of moving the liquid hose from rear pull tank to front tank.    As the driver was moving the liquid hose from the rear pull tank to the front tank the auxillary pump motor stoped and the backflow device was non-operational causing approximately the spillage of three gallons Aqua Ammonia.    Upon the accidental release the driver imeadiately shut down the delivery pump valve closing the source of release.     The pump was immediately taken out of service and repaired with a new rubber back flow devise. THe rest of the product was safely unloaded.
column169: All mechanics involved in the repair or maintenance have recieved new procedures to annualy check to ensure the back flow devise is in place and is opperational as well as requirement to place the pump "motor out of service" if a back flow device fails, and can not be returned until new backflow device is installed.    All the drivers that are required to operate any of the pump motors have recieved additonal training that clearly states under no circumstance can the driver or any one else remove the back flow devise and the pump motor must be placed "out of service" until a qualified mechanic and repair or replace the back flow device.

column168: THIS IS YET ANOTHER INSTANCE OF OVERFILLING AN ABOVEGROUND OIL STORAGE TANK WHEN USING THE POWER TAKE OFF TRACTOR PUMP OF THE DELIVERING UNIT.  THIS PARTICULAR TANK HAS A RATED CAPACITY OF 20,000 GALLONS.  IT IS UPRIGHT ABOUT FORTY FEET HIGH WITH NO MEANS OF MANUALLY GAGING THE PRODUCT INSIDE THE TANK.  TANK READINGS FOR THIS TANK ARE REMOTELY LOCATED INSIDE AN ADJACENT MAINTAINENCE BUILDING.  ACCORDING TO THE VULCAN EMPLOYEE WHO ORDERED THE OIL SHIPMENT HIS GAUGE SHOWED 3,000 GALLONS IN THE TANK SO HE ORDERED 15,000 GALLONS.  AFTER OIL TRANSPORT DRIVER PUMPED 13,000 GALLONS INTO THE TANK THE TANK OVERFILLED AND PRODUCT CAME OUT THE TOP VENT SYSTEM.  PRODUCT RAN DOWN THE SIDE OF THE STORAGE TANK INTO THE CONCRETE CONTAINMENT AREA SURROUNDING THE ABOVE GROUND TANK.  THE OIL TRANSPORT DRIVER USED HIS TRUCK PUMP TO EVACUATE THE SPILLED PRODUCT FROM INSIDE THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND PUMPED IT INTO AN EMPTY TRAILER COMPARTMENT WHERE IT WAS LATER DISPOSED OF.  THERE WAS NO EQUIPMENT FAILURE ON THE PART OF THE DELIVERING CARRIER.
column169: GENERALLY SPEAKING, CARRIERS ARE AT THE MERCY OF THE RECEIVING UNIT - PARTY TO PROVIDE CORRECT INFORMATION CONCERNING WHETHER OR NOT THEIR TANK WILL HOLD THE AMOUNT WHICH THEY ORDERED AND WHICH THE CARRIER IS ATTEMPTING TO DELIVER.  I WOULD RECOMMEND THAT COMPANIES WITH STORAGE TANKS HAVE AN ALTERNATE METHOD OF DETERMINING PRODUCT LEVELS INSIDE THEIR STORAGE TANKS, OR PERHAPS INSTALLATION OF OVERFILL ALARMS WHEN PRODUCT LEVEL REACHES A CERTAIN PERCENTAGE.

column168: WHEN THE DRIVER STARTED OR ENGAGED THE PUMP, THE HOSE FITTING POPPED OUT OF THE FILL BOX AT THE CURB.  HE WAS ABLE TO RECONNECT USING A DIFFERENT FITTING AND COMPLETED THE DELIVERY.

column168: AT 1525 HOURS ON APRIL 2ND TANK CAR GATX81871 WAS REPORTED LEAKING A SLOW DRIP OF PRODUCT AT OUR CSX TRANSPORTATION'S AUGUSTA YARD.  CSX MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATION'S TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  THE AREA AROUND THE RAIL CAR WAS ISOLATED.  THE SHIPPER / CONSIGNEE, PENRECO WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC.  HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND AND CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  A PLASTIC BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF THE RAILCAR TO COLLECT THE LEAKING PETROLEUM DISTILLATE.  INVESTIGATION REVEALS THE CAR WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM AROUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE MOUNTING FLANGE PLATE.  HEPACO REPRESENTATIVES WERE UNABLE TO TIGHTEN THE HEX HEAD BOLTS.  RESCAR SERVICES WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND AND WAS ALSO UNABLE TO SECURE THE RELEASE.  THE SHIPPER WAS AGAIN NOTIFIED AND PROVIDED RESIDUE TANK CAR GATX50621 FOR TRANSFER OF THE COMMODITY.  HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL COMPLETED THE TRANSFER AND THE NEWLY LOADED CAR WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.  PENRECO WILL SUBMIT THE REQUIRED FEDERAL RAILROAD ADMINISTRATION MOVEMENT EXEMPTION TO FORWARD THE DEFECTIVE CONTAINER TO A REPAIR FACILITY.  AT THIS TIME WE BELIEVE THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY A DETERIORATED BOTTOM OUTLET MOUNTING FLANGE GASKET.  APPROXIMATELY FIVE (5) GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE RAIL CAR.  THIS PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH PADS AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF AT A LOCAL LANDFILL.

ON 4/11/05 AT 10:46 HOURS, THE TRAINMASTER AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S QUEENSGATE YARD IN CINCINNATI, OHIO, ADVISED THAT PERSONNEL IN THE YARD REPORTED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA.  THERE WERE TWO RESIDUE ANHYDROUS AMMONIA CARS IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY.  CSXT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT THE CARS.  THE CONTRACTOR, SUMMIT ENVIRONMENTAL, INSPECTED TANK CAR, PLMX 135078 AND DISCOVERED THAT BOTH LIQUID ANGLE VALVES AND THE VAPOR ANGLE VALVE WERE OPEN AND THE THREE VALVE PLUGS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  SUMMIT REPORTED THAT THERE WAS NO PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND NO VAPOR RELEASE WHEN THEY INSPECTED THE CAR.  THEY CLOSED THE VALVES AND INSTALLED THE VALVE PLUGS WRENCH TIGHT.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER, SABINA FARMERS EXCHANGE AND THE CONSIGNEE, TRANSAMMONIA WERE NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.
column169: HAVE BEEN IN CONTACT WITH THE SHIPPER SABINA FARMERS EXCHANGE ABOUT PROPERLY CLOSING VALVES AND REPLACING PLUGS ON HIGH PRESSURE TANK CARS.

column168: THE DMT TANK TRUCK LOADING PROCESS INVOLVES TWO OPERATORS.  ONCE THE TANK TRUCK IS HOOKED UP AND READY TO BE LOADED, ONE OPERATOR GOES INSIDE THE BUILDING TO OPERATE AND MONITOR THE DMT LOADING METER.  THE OTHER OPERATOR OBSERVED THE TANK TRUCK WHILE IT IS LOADING.  WHILE SUPERIOR 46728 WAS LOADING, THE OUTSIDE OPERATOR OBSERVED DMT EXITING THE VENT LINE ON THE TANK TRUCK.  AT ONCE THEY NOTIFIED THE INSIDE OPERATOR WHO WAS MONITORING THE LOADING METER.  LOADING WAS IMMEDIATELY HALTED.  ALL MANUAL VALVES IN THE LOADING LINE AND ON THE TRAILER WERE CLOSED.  THE LOADING METER HAD NOT YET REACHED THE TARGET WEIGHT, BUT THE TANK TRUCK WAS OVERLOADED.  THE OPERATORS CLEANED UP THE DISCHARGE.  FOLLOWING ARE EXAMPLES OF HOW THE EFFECTS OF THE RELEASE WERE MITIGATED: TWO OPERATORS WERE AVAILABLE TO OBSERVE THE LOADING PROCESS, THE OPERATORS WERE FOLLOWING PROCEDURES, THE SPILL WENT TO A CONTAINED AREA, AND THE PUMP WAS IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF WHEN THE SPILL WAS DETECTED.
column169: THE LOADING OPERATOR REDUCED THE TARGET WEIGHT ON THE LOADING METER BY APPROXIMATELY 5000 POUNDS TO PREVENT ANOTHER SPILL FROM OCCURRING UNTIL THE LOADING METER COULD BE CHECKED, DMT OPERATIONS HAD MAINTENANCE TO EXAMINE THE LOADING METER TO SEE WHY IT HAD MALFUNCTIONED.  MAINTENANCE NOTICED SOME FLUCTUATION IN THE LOADING METER WHILE LOADING ANOTHER DMT TRAILER.  MAINTENANCE CALIBRATED THE LOADING METER.

THE PACKAGE DID NOT CONTAIN ANY HAZARDOUS MARKINGS INDICATING IT CONTAINED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL.  CARDINAL HEALTH HAS SINCE INFORMED US THAT THE DIVISION THAT OFFERED THIS SHIPMENT WAS SOLD IN DECEMBER 2004 TO FLUKE BIOMEDICAL RMS.

column169: Employees are coached to follow our policies of ignition key control and performing a complete walk-around of the vehicle before moving it. Employees who fail to follow our policies are often times required to write and present a safety meeting to their peers covering the infraction they committed. A pull-away is regarded as a very serious offense, therefore have a greater potential for more severe disciplinary actions.

column168: Consignee showed driver which tank to deliver to and signed drivers paperwork that he was hooked up properly.  Driver unloaded 1600 gal and thought the delivery was completed without any problems.  3 days later the customer called to say that the driver delivered to the wrong tank and the tank overflowed.  Not sure how much.  It went into a containment area that leads to plant system.  Customer asked that we get a clean up firm out there to pump out the tank and clean it and the containment area. They said whoever signed driver's paperwork did not have authority to do so. Customer was able to use some of the contaminated product from the top of the tank but the bottom part started to gell so we had to arrange disposal of it.
column169: We have a system in place to match BOL, with all tank #'s and tag #'s.  Driver has received remedial to make sure that everything matches and if he has any questions to call in before he takes another step.  He said he was being rushed by rude plant personnel.

column168: Driver had completed transferring product from cargo tank to customer storage tank.  He bled the pressure off of the line but there must have been a little pressure still left in the line. When he disconnected hose from customer tank, a mist came out and got under his face shield on to his chin.  He immediately went to shower for 15 minutes.  Plant personnel then took him to plant clinic to be checked out and he was told to shower again.  We had driver go to the clinic then to make sure he was okay.  Doctor gave him some cream and he was released.  He had 2 small blisters on his chest supposedly from where it ran off chin when he showered.  Driver had on full PPE to include chemical suit when incident occurred.
column169: Reinforce training to make sure drivers understand that even with correct PPE, safety needs to be their #1 focus.  Keep their head down and keep the faceshield between the product and their face.

column168: A DRIVER EMPLOYED BY HYDRO-WALK ENERGY, INC. LOADED A FULL LOAD OF 8500 GALS. OF GASOLINE AT SUNSHINE TERMINAL IN MONROE, LA WHICH WAS SUPPOSED TO BE DELIVERED TO BROOKSHIRES STORE ON CROSSETT, AR.  INSTEAD, THE DRIVER ABANDONED THE TRUCK AN LOAD ON GIROD STREET IN MONROE, LA.  PEOPLE BEGAN TO STEAL GASOLINE FROM THE TANK TRAILER BY LOADING PLASTIC BUCKETS WITH GASOLINE.  A CITIZEN CALLED THE MONROE POLICE DEPARTMENT AND WHEN THE OFFICER ARRIVED ON THE SCENE HE SAW SEVERAL PEOPLE STEALING THE GASOLINE.  IN THE PROCESS THE THIEVES SPILLED APPROX. 20 GALS OF GASOLINE IN THE ROADSIDE DITCH.  ONE PERSON WAS ARRESTED.  THE TRUCK DRIVER HAS NOT BEEN LOCATED.  THE POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS BLOCKED OFF THE AREA AND EVACUATED APPROX. 5 PEOPLE.  A CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS HIRED TO PUMP OUT THE DITCH AND THEN DIG UP THE SOIL IN THE DITCH.  THE ENTIRE TIME FROM SPILL TO COMPLETION OF THE CLEAN UP WAS APPROX. 5 HOURS.
column169: THIS INCIDENT WAS UNPREDICTABLE AND THE FIRST SUCH INCIDENT IN THE TWENTY FIVE YEAR HISTORY OF THE COMPANY.

column168: A CTMV containing a non hazardous material lost control, left the roadway, crashed into and knocked down an 8’ highway sign and then overturned in the ditch. Highway Transport, Inc vehicle (reporting motor carrier) slowed and stopped in traffic due to the sign being in the roadway. A flat bed CMV transporting drilling pipe failed to stop, crashing into the right rear of the Highway Transport, Inc CTMV and the left rear of an SUV, lost control, overturned and caught fire in the ditch.  Both driver and passenger in flatbed CMV died as a result of the crash and fire.     Roadway was closed, not because of Hazardous Material, but because of a fatality accident and drilling pipe which covered the roadway. Once roadway was cleared State Police escorted Highway Transport, Inc CTMV from the accident scene.     Highway Transport, Inc CTMV sustained damage to right rear bumper and trailer axle and wheels and tires. Insulation and outer sheeting were also damaged; however there was no damage to the barrel of this cargo tank and no release of material.
column169: It is unclear as to what action the Highway Transport, Inc driver could have taken to avoid this collision. Another CMV operator had stopped at the scene of the first accident and was trying to slow traffic and move traffic into the left lane. The Highway Transport, Inc driver moved into the left lane and stopped in traffic before running over the highway sign lying in the roadway. It was reported that at least 4 automobiles had ran over the sign and each had flat tires.

CAUSE OF THIS DERAILMENT WAS EXCESSIVE BUFFING OR SLACK ACTION DUE TO TRAIN MAKE-UP, AS TWO OF THESE RAILCARS ADJACENT TO CCBX 5223 WERE EMPTY INTERMODAL FLATCARS WITH ONE OF THESE FLATCARS INCURRING WHEEL LIFT AT A SWITCH TO A TRACK TURNOUT.  CCBX 5223 DERAILED UP RIGHT, BUT THE BOTTOM OPRATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS SHEARED-OFF AND THIS OULET'S BUTTERFLY VALVE PARTIALLY OPENED.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS CLOSED THE VALVE BY 1527 HRS. CDT, 4/12/05, ENDING PRODUCT RELEASE.  CCBX 5223 WAS RERAILED AND REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER SUITABLE TANK CAR.  CONTRACT RESPONDERS HAND EXCAVATED PRODUCT CONTAMINATED BALLAST AND SOIL, PLACING EXCAVATED MATERIAL INTO A DISPOSAL DRUM TO BE TAKEN TO THE BFI MCCARTY ROAD LANDFILL.

column168: A BETTENDORF CITY EMPLOYEE REPORTED A BNSF ENTRAINED COVERED HOPPER (ATSF 314628) LEAKING COMMODITY FROM ONE OF THE BOTTOM HOPPER OUTLET GATES.  THE BNSF TRAIN WAS STOPPED AT 26TH STREET FROM BETTENDORF AND THE LOCAL F.D. RESPONDERS ATTEMPTED TO CLOSE THE 'C' HOPPER BOTTOM OUTLET (THE MIDDLE OUTLET ON A THREE OUTLET CONFIGURATION) THAT HAD OPENED LESS THAN TWO INCHES AND WAS SPILLING PRODUCT.  THEY WERE LATER JOINED BY MECHANICAL RESPONDERS FROM THE IOWA, CHICAGO & EASTERN RAILROAD (ICE RR).  RESPONDERS CLOSED THE BOTTOM OUTLET PRIOR TO 1330 HRS. CDT AND ICE RR MECHANICAL RESPONDERS FORCED WOODEN WEDGES AROUND THIS OUTLET TO PREVENT ANOTHER UNINTENTIONAL OPENING.  THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE UNINTENTIONAL OPENING IS UNKNOWN, AFTER SECUREMENT COMPLETED, ATSF 314628 WAS INTERCHANGED TO THE ICE RR FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.  A TRAIL OF PRODUCT WAS FOUND STARTING AT 31ST STREET WHICH ENDED AT 26TH STREET WHERE THE ATSF 314628 WAS INITIALLY STOPPED AND SECURED.  A BNSF ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR VACUUMED ALL SPILLAGE IN BETTENDORF UTILIZING A VAC-TRUCK.  BACKTRACKING, ADDITIONAL PRODUCT WAS FOUND IN THE BNSF RAILYARD IN BARSTOW, IL. AND THIS SPILLAGE WAS ALSO VACUUMED-UP.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO PROVIDE A LOCAL FARMER WITH THE RECOVERED PRODUCT TO FERTILIZE HIS FARM FIELDS.

The driver arrived at the customers facility, checked in with the plant operator, received authorization to unload, the customer verfied the tank level and the driver was given authorization to perform the unloading process. 3/4 of the way through the unloading process the tank reached its full capacity and product was released through a vent pipe to the outside onto a concrete pad. The tank is inside a building requiring the customer to monitor the tank level. The plant operator must notify the driver when he needs to stop the product flow from the cargo tank. The plant operator failed to monitor the tank properly. The customer took full responsibility for the overflow and performed the required clean up. Approx. 4 to 6 gallons reached a concrete pad and the balance of the product was contained in 5 gallon buckets. The balance of the product was unloaded into another storage tank at the customer facility without further incident.
column169: Some type of alarm system would be helpful when the customers tank reaches a certain level to limit the release of product when the driver has no way to monitor or observe the tank.

column168: Univar driver was making a delivery.  When he opened the back of his trailer he had to move a drum off the trailer onto the customer dock in order to get at the customer freight.  The driver moved the single drum with a drum dolly and placed it on the customer dock.  The driver and unloader noticed a small wet spot on the trailer.  The driver noticed that the drum that he had put on the customer dock was leaking.  The driver turned the drum on it's side and put it back on the trailer.  The customer responded to the leaking drum, cleaning up product and placing material and drum in an overpak.  During the clean-up operation the customer evacuated their facility.  Four customer employees and one Univar employee were check at the local clinic and released.   The drum chime was damaged/cut by some sharp object.  It could not be determined when the chime was damaged.
column169: Drum pallets and trailers are inspected for nails prior to use.

column168: ON APRIL 22, 2005, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY KLLM WAS PARKED AT THE TA TRUCKSTOP IN JEFFERSON, OHIO.  THE DRIVER NOTICED A SMALL PAINT LEAK LEAKING FROM THE DRAIN HOLE OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER'S BILL OF LADING INDICATED THAT SEVERAL TOTES OF PAINT RELATED MATERIALS WERE ON BOARD.  ON APRIL 22, 2005, CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) WAS CONTACTED BY KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES TO MANAGE THE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT.  CES CONTACTED THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR-TRAILER TO GAIN SUPPORTING INFORMATION ON THIS RELEASE.  THE DRIVER INDICATED THAT HE NOTICED A SMALL, SLOW LEAK COMING FROM THE TRAILER AND HE HAD PLUGGED THE HOLE WITH PAPER TOWEL IN EFFORTS TO STOP THE LEAK.  THE DRIVER DID NOT KNOW HOW MUCH PAINT HAD RELEASED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  BASED ON THE INFORMATION GIVEN, CES DISPATCHED A CREW FROM PRO-TERRA TO PERFORM CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ON SITE.  ON APRIL 22, 2005 PRO-TERRA MOBILIZED TO THE SITE AND OPENED THE TRAILER.  THE CREW OBSERVED A SMALL PORTION OF THE RELEASE ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  IT APPEARED THAT THE DRAIN VALVE ON THE LEAKING TOTE WAS IN THE OPEN POSITION.  APPARENTLY THE SEAL ON THE VALVE WAS FAULTY SO THE CREW REPLACED THE VALVE COMPLETELY.  THE VALVE WAS CLOSED AND THE TRAILER WAS WIPED DOWN.  THE CREW COLLECTED ALL OF THE RELEASED MATERIAL AND SPENT ABSORBENTS IN TWO 55-GALLON BUCKETS AND PREPARED IT FOR DISPOSAL.

ON APRIL 6, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30 P.M. CDT, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY KLLM TRUCKING WAS ENTERING A PILOT TRUCK STOP ON INTERSTATE 81 AT EXIT 52B WHEN A PALLET COLLAPSED IN THE TRAILER CAUSING A DRUM OF CYCLOHEXYLAMINE TO BE PUNCTURED.  AS A RESULT OF THE PUNCTURE IN THE DRUM, APPROXIMATELY 4 GALLONS OF CYCLOHEXYLAMINE WAS RELEASED ONTO THE ASPHALT PARKING LOT.  THE PENNSYLVANIA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION, CARLISLE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM INITIALLY RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT.  ON APRIL 6, 2005, MS. GINGER CARTER OF KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES CONTACTED CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) TO MANAGE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT.  CES WAS INFORMED THAT A LIQUID WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR CORNERS OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER ESTIMATED THAT 5 GALLONS OF CYCLOHEXYLAMINE WAS RELEASED.  BASED ON THE INFORMATION GIVEN, CES DISPATCHED A CREW FROM HMHTTC TO PERFORM A SITE ASSESSMENT AND NECESSARY CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE RESPONSE CREW FROM HMHTTC ARRIVED ONSITE AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30 P.M. CDT AND MET WITH REPRESENTATIVES.  THE COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM WAS PREPARING TO MAKE FIRST ENTRY AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THEY WOULD CONTINUE WITH HMHTTC CREWS AS SUPPORT PERSONNEL.  THE CREW ISOLATED THE IMPACTED DRUM AND TRANSFERRED IT INTO AN OVERPACK.  THE COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM THEN DEMOBILIZED AND TURNED THE SITE OVER TO HMHTTC TO FINISH THE NECESSARY CORRECTIVE ACTIONS.  THE ASPHALT WAS CLEANED USING AN AMMONIA AND WATER SOLUTION TO THE SATISFACTION OF TRUCK STOP MANAGEMENT.  THE TRUCK WAS THEN SECURED FOR THE EVENING AT THE HMHTTC WAREHOUSE SO THAT THE CARGO COULD BE OFFLOADED AND PROPERLY DECONTAMINATED.  THE CREW FROM HMHTTC RETURNED TO SITE THE NEXT MORNING.  THE CARGO WAS OFFLOADED AND EACH DRUM WAS WASHED WITH A NEUTRALIZING SOLUTION. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Forklift Accident
column168: Two lead acid fork truck batteries, about 2500 lbs each, were shipped to maintenance at IBM Tucson, building 9016. Upon opening the rock to unload, the receiving attendant noticed that the batteries had shifted in the truck and on the pallets during uansportation. One battery was tilted at an angle and leaning against anather battery. The pallet was damaged. The driver acknowledged that the load had shifted violently when he made left turn.  While the chemical attendant was using the fork truck to push the battery to an upright position and moves it to an undamaged pallet, the battery tipped and fell on its side. Approximately one gallon of electrolyte leaked slowly from the battery vents.  The incident was reported using the on-site 3911 emergency number. The on-site spill response team arrived and applied neutralizer to the electrolyte that spilled out of the truck into the dock well. The fork truck was used to put the battery in a upright position. The trailer was moved a short distance from th.e dock. Thn resDonse team entered the truck, applied neutralizer, and used hoses to wash the interior of the trailer and the battery. The ninsate, tested and found to be neitral, was drained to the B/9016 containment vault and will be treated at the on-site industrial waste waler treatrntnt plant.  The battery was inspected and found not damaged. It was banded to a new pallet, placed back in the truck, secured and blocked to pre’ent shifting during transportation, and returned to the supplier.
column169: The shipper and carrier were be reminded to properly secure the batteries to prevent movement during tranrportation.

column168: DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS, THE CARRIER'S EMPLOYEES OBSERVED LIQUID SPLASH FROM THE TOP OF TANK CAR UTLX 57979 IN THE AREA OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.  MOVEMENT OF THE CAR WAS HALTED AND THE APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE CARRIER CONTACTED BOTH THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE.  THE CONSIGNEE DISPATCHED EMPLOYEES TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE TANK CAR.  THE CONSIGNEE EMPLOYEES FOUND THAT THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) WAS NOT FUNCTIONING PROPERLY AND THAT IT WAS NOT VAPOR OR LIQUID TIGHT, THUS ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE IF THE CAR WAS MOVED.  THE CONSIGNEE'S EMPLOYEES DID NOT HAVE THE APPROPRIATE TOOLS OR TRAINING TO CORRECT THE DEFECTIVE CONDITION.  THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST INSPECTED THE PRD AND FOUND THAT THE RETAINING CLIP AND LOCK NUT THAT HOLD THE VALVE SPRING WERE MISSING.  IN EFFECT, THERE WAS NO TENSION ON THE VALVE SPRING AND NO MECHANICAL ATTACHMENT BETWEEN THE O-RING RETAINING CAP AND THE VALVE BODY.  THIS CONDITION ALLOWED LIQUID PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FOR THE VALVE IF LIQUID WERE TO IMPACT AGAINST THE TOP OF THE VALVE (O-RING RETAINING CAP).  THE CARRIER ADVISED THE SHIPPER OF THE CONDITIONS FOUND AND OF THE NEED FOR A CERTIFIED TANK CAR REPAIR SHOP TO REPLACE THE DEFECTIVE VALVE.  THE SHIPPER CONTACTED RESCAR OF ELK MILLS, MD.  [AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT, THE REPAIR FIRM HAD NOT YET RECEIVED THE NECESSARY PARTS TO REPAIR/REPLACE THE VALVE.  THE CAR IS BEING HELD AT THE CARRIER'S YARD UNTIL THE PRD IS REPAIRED.]
column169: BETTER INSPECTION OF TANK CAR COMPONENTS BY SHIPPER PRIOR TO RELEASE OF CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  PROPER INSPECTION OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE MAY HAVE REVEALED THE DEFECT PRIOR TO TRANSPORTATION.

BNSF ROADSWITCHER PULLING OUT OF INDUSTRY/SIDING TRACK ONTO THE BNSF MAINLINE DERAILED SEVEN RAILCARS AT THE MAIN TRACK SWITCH.  FOUR OF THESE RAILCARS WERE TANK CARS OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  TWO OF THESE THAT DERAILED ON THEIR SIDES, LEAKED A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT.  UTLX 202636 DERAILED ON ITS SIDE AND DRIPPED PRODUCT FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE (VRV).  A BUCKET WAS PLACED UNDER THE VRV TO CATCH DRIPPINGS AND THE VRV WAS TAPED TO EBB THE FLOW OF THE RELEASE.  ANY ADDITIONAL PRODUCT RELEASE ENDED WHEN UTLX 202636 WAS UPRIGHTED.  DUE TO EQUIPMENT DAMAGES, THE REMAINING PRODUCT IN UTLX 202636 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANKER TRUCKS ON 4/19 AND 4/20 FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.
column169: NO ADDITIONAL COMMENTS.

column168: DRAYMAN PICKING UP INTERMODAL CONTAINER HDMU 206606 FROM THE BNSF INTERMODAL PARKING LOT, REPORTED THIS CONTAINER LEAKING A LIQUID SUBSTANCE FROM THE CONTAINER'S DOORWAY THRESHOLD.  HDMU 206606 WAS TAKEN TO THE CONTAINMENT AREA.  BNSF CONTRACT RESPONDERS OBSERVED SEVERAL CORROSION HOLES IN THIS CONTAINERS ROOF, SIDEWALLS AND DOORWAY.  THESE HOLES ALLOWED WATER TO ENTER THE CONTAINER AND SATURATE SEVERAL BAGS OF PRODUCT INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  THREE BAGS WERE FOUND TO HAVE CUTS/TEARS TO THE PLASTIC BAGS.  THE BAGS WERE ALSO WRAPPED ON THE OUTSIDE WITH PLASTIC AND EACH BAG WAS ON A WOODED PALLET AND STACKED.  THE BAGS WERE LIKELY CUT OR TORN DURING MOVEMENT OF THE LADING IN TRANSIT.  THE WATER MIXED WITH THE EXPOSED DRY PRODUCT IN THE COMPROMISED BAGS AND AS THIS PRODUCT IS SOLUABLE IN WATER, PRODUCED A LIQUID MIXTURE OF DILUTED PRODUCT THAT ACCUMULATED ON THE OTHER BAGS AND THE CONTAINER FLOOR.  RESPONDERS REMOVED ALL LADING INSIDE HDMU 206606 AND NEUTRALIZED SPILLAGE.  THE THREE DAMAGED BAGS WERE SET ASIDE AND THE NON-DAMAGED BAGS WERE WIPED, REWRAPPED IN PLASTIC AND TRANSFERRED TO OTHER INTERMODAL CONTAINERS FOR FURTHERANCE TO DESTINATION.  DISPOSAL OF THE DAMAGED BAGS AND CLEANING MATERIALS IS PENDING.
column169: ENSURE SHIPPER INSPECTS AND SELECTS SUITABLE INTERMODAL CONTAINERS/TRAILERS THAT HAVE THE STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY TO TRANSPORT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, AS WELL AS, OTHER LADING.  ALSO, SHIPPER NEEDS TO PROPERLY BLOCK AND BRACE LADING FOR TRANSPORTATION
column172: Plastic, coated with liner, for solids

column168: CN SWITCH CREW SWITCHED ELEVEN CARS TOWARD TRACK GL20 AT THE CN GLENN YARD, CHICAGO, IL. CARS TRUCK TANK CAR GATX 29936 WHICH WAS STOPPED IN THE CURVE AND FOULING TRACK GL02. DRAWBARS BY-PASSED AND CARS CORNERED CAUSING THE A-END COUPLER OF TANK UTLX 640311 TO PUNCTURE THE LOWER LEFT SIDE TANK SHELL OF GATX 29936, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ESCAPE. ALL APPROPRIATE DEPARTMENTS WERE NOTIFIED, LOCAL HAZMAT TEAM ORDERED A YARD OPERATION STOPAGE AND SHELTER IN PLACE FOR CN EMPLOYEES AT THE GLENN YARD OFFICES. NO EVACUTION OR OTHER SHELTER IN PLACE ORDERED. TEMPORARY REPAIRS MADE TO GATX 29936 TO SLOW LOSS OF PRODUCT. ALL REMAINING PRODUCT TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CAR NATX 301107.

column168: ONE OF OUR PICKUP TRUCKS WAS PULLING TWO ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TANKS BACK TO THE FACILITY FOR FILLING WHEN THE DRIVER FAILED TO STOP PRIOR TO CROSSING THE BNSF RAILROAD TRACKS AT THE ENTRANCE TO OUR FACILITY.  A PASSING LOCOMOTIVE STRUCK THE REAR NURSE TANK.  THE IMPACT CAUSED AN APPROXIMATELY 6" GOUGE IN THE TANK HEAD AND CAUSED THE NURSE TANK TO OVERTURN ONTO ITS SIDE.  THE NURSE TANK REMAINED HITCHED TO THE TOWING UNIT DURING THE ACCIDENT.  THERE WAS A SHORT RAPID DISPERSION OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA VAPOR FROM THE GOUGE IN THE TANK.  THREE TRAIN CREW MEMBERS AND ONE EMPLOYEE WERE EVALUATED BY AMBULANCE PERSONNEL AT THE SCENE BUT ALL REFUSED TREATMENT.
column169: DRIVER TRAINING MUST RE-ENFORCE THE LAW REQUIRING ALL LOADS CARRYING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ARE TO STOP PRIOR TO CROSSING RAILROAD TRACKS.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: ON WEDNESDAY, APRIL 13, 2005, THE DRIVER FOR COVENANT TRANSPORT DISCOVERED A LEAK AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  HE IMMEDIATELY CALLED HIS CORPORATE OFFICE TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  THE CORPORATE OFFICE DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CREW IMMEDIATELY.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SITE THE RESPONSE CREW NOTED A SMALL DRIP COMING THROUGH THE TRAILER FLOOR AT THE REAR END OF THE TRAILER.  ON OPENING THE DOOR A PALLET OF BOXES CONTAINING 2.5 GALLON JUGS OF PAINT THINNER WAS NOTICED TO BE WET.  THE CONTAINERS WERE ALL REMOVED FROM THE BOXES AND INSPECTED.  TWO JUGS WERE FOUND TO HAVE CAPS THAT HAD BEEN CROSS-THREADED OR NOT COMPLETELY FASTENED.  THE MOVEMENT OF THE TRUCKS HAD CAUSED THE PAINT THINNER TO SPILL THROUGH THE LOOSE CAPS.  THE LIDS ON THE TWO CONTAINERS WERE RE-FASTENED SO NO MORE MARKING WOULD OCCUR.  THE REST OF THE CARGO WAS INSPECTED AND NO LEAKS WERE FOUND.  THERE WERE NO FREE LQIUIDS ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER OR ON THE ASPHALT DUE TO THE RAPID EVAPORATION RATE OF PAINT THINNER.  THE TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO AIR OUT FOR A PERIOD OF TIME BEFORE THE DRIVER RESUMED HIS DELIVERY.  THE ENTIRE RESPONSE AND CLEANUP LASTED FOR A PERIOD OF 3-4 HOURS.
column169: COVENANT TRANSPORT HAS SPOKEN TO THE SHIPPER ABOUT THE PROBLEM WITH THE CLOSURE OF THE LIDS AND REQUESTED CORRECTION OF THE PROBLEM.

column62: Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER WAS PULLING AN ANHYDROUS AMMONIA NURSE TRAILER WITH A PICKUP ON A DIRT COUNTY ROAD.  TRAILER WITH 4,000 LB STEEL TANK (PRODUCT CAPACITY) BEGAN TO WHIP & SWERVE.  ESTIMATED SPEED WAS 30-35 MPH.  DRIVER SLAMMED ON BRAKES IN AN ATTEMPT TO STOP.  WHEN BRAKES WERE APPLIED.  THE TRAILER JACK KNIFED & HIT THE SIDES OF THE PICKUP BED.  THIS CAUSED THE PORTABLE TANK TO BREAK LOOSE FROM THE TRAILER AND ROLL INTO THE DITCH.  AS THE TANK HIT THE GROUND & ROLLED, THE STEEL SAFETY CAGE SMASHED IN CAUSING THE VALVES AND GAUGES TO BREAK LOOSE.  THIS CAUSE THE PRODUCT UNDER PRESSURE TO RELEASE INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  WATER MIST WAS APPLIED TO NH3 BY THE FIRE DEPT. TO KEEP THE LIQUID AMMONIA FROM ACCUMULATING.  NO INJURIES OR PROPERLY DMG WERE NOTED.
column169: CONDUCT ADDITIONAL TRAINING TO INCLUDE THE FOLLOWING: 1.  ALWAYS EVALUATE ROAD CONDITIONS & ADJUST SPEED ACCORDING TO THOSE ROAD CONDITIONS.  2.  IF TRAILERS BEGIN TO WHIP FROM SIDE TO SIDE, DO NOT OVER-REACT BY OVERBRAKING.  BRING TO GRADUAL STOP BY LETTING UP ON GAS & LIGHT BRAKING.

column14: FOOT OF AVENUE F/168 SOUTH BAY
column168: 4:00PM, TUESDAY, APRIL 19, 2005: DURING A ROUTINE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTION, FRA HAZARDOUS MATERIAL INSPECTOR R. DEDOW NOTED TANK CAR ACFX 75123, LOAD METHANOL, WITH A VERY MINOR LEAK ORIGINATING FROM THE TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE OPERATING ROD ON TOP OF THE CAR.  MR. DEDOW REPORTED AN OCCASSIONAL DRIP OF LIQUID, ALONG WITH VAPOR, WAS ORIGINATING FROM UNDER THE PACKING GLAND NUT FOR THE OPERATING ROD OF SAID VALVE.  MR. DEDOW REPORTED THE ICNIDENT TO THE YARDMASTER, WHO IN TURN CALLED THE LOCAL SHIPPER, IMTT, BAYONNE, NJ, AND N. FERRONE, DIRECTOR RISK MANAGEMENT, CR.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY IMTT AND REACT ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (REQUESTED BY CR) NOTED THE PACKING GLAND NUT FOR THE TOP OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOTTOM OUTLET WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT.  ADDITIONALLY, FURTHER INSPECTION BY REACT NOTED THE PACKING GLAND NUTS FOR THE VALVE OPERATING STEMS ON BOTH THE CLOSED SYSTEM LIQUID AND AIR VALVES WERE EXTREMELY LOOSE.  ALL FITTINGS WERE MADE SECURED AS REQUIRED.  CAR OKAYED TO BE SHIPPED AT APPROXIMATELY 8PM.  **NOTE: REPORTED BY FRA INSPECTOR R. DEDOW; AS THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT CONTACTED AIR AND THE CAR, IT IMMEDIATELY EVAPORATED, RESULTING IN NO ENVIRONMENTAL MITIGATION BEING REQUIRED.

column168: Email from Employee about that night     Dave,     On the night of 04/30/05, a ms. Louise Taylor, employee of Alaska Airlines since 01/05/99, tendered a shipment of household goods comprised largely of printed matters and folded up boxes.  When she arrived, I was on the phone with a customer and so had Kristian get a weight and piece count of the shipment.  When i finished on the phone, I helped him to count, weigh, inspect, and get the dimensions of all forty-seven pieces.  We inspected twenty percent of the shipment (ten pieces) and everything seemed fine.  It wasn't until after the customer left, while I was affixing lot labels to the boxes, that I noticed the words "cleaning supplies" and "matches" written on the side of one box.  Knowing that "cleaning supplies" is a trigger term for possibly undisclosed dangerous goods and that matches are not allowed on passenger aircrafts unless safety matches, I felt it necessary to open the box for further inspection.  Upon opening it, I discovered cleaning agents in compressed aerosol cans, hygrogen peroxide, bug spray, laundry detergent etc. and matches.  I knew that such things are not allowed to be shipped as cargo unless all precautions are taken to properly ship them as dangerous goods and indeed this is not the case. Being my first time dealing with undisclosed dangerous goods discovered after the customer has departed, I perused the IATA handbook for several of the chemicals discovered and realized they certainly are not acceptable for transport in the condition tendered.  For guidance in this particular situation, I turned to Maria who happened to be in the cargo facility at the moment.  She informed me that this could be a very big deal requiring the invovlement of the TSA and FAA.  It was at this moment that you called and I informed you of the situation.     As instructed, I telephoned the customer to let her know that the box was unacceptable for transport.  Unfortunately, I misspoke and told her we could also dispose of it with her approval.  When i learned that this is in fact untrue, I called her back and told her she would have to come back to take the package and watch us inspect each piece in the rest of her shipment.  She politely expressed her unwillingness to return and I informed her that it would be much easier on all involved if she could make the time.  I continued to explain that if she did not, the issue could become much larger and we may be forced to contact the TSA and FAA regarding the discovery of undisclosed dangerous goods.  She very calmly told me to do what we must.
column169: All agents have been asked to start looking more closely at the writing on the boxes to look for trigger items wrote on boxes    Alaska Station Manager and Supervisors where let know at the frist point and have been aware the everything we have done

column168: ON APRIL 19, 2005 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:30 PM, PWIS DRIVER ALFRED EASTMAN AFTER COMPLETING A TURN ONTO STATE COLLEGE BLVD NOTICED MATERIAL LEAKING FROM HIS TANKER.  HE IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  MATERIAL WAS LEAKING FROM THE TANK, A PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE THAT HAD BEEN LEFT SLIGHTLY OPEN.  HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVE AND RADIOED THE WORK SITE HE HAD JUST DEPARTED FROM, (ABOUT 1 MILE AWAY) AND REQUESTED CLEAN-UP ASSISTANCE.  ALL PERSONNEL QUICKLY DROVE TO THE SPILL LOCATION.  ABSORBENTS WERE USED TO CONTROL THE SPILLAGE (ALL SPILLAGE WAS CONFINED TO THE ROADWAY, NONE OF THE MATERIAL MIGRATED OFF-SITE, OR INTO STORM SEWERS.) A PASSING ANAHEIM POLICE OFFICER STOPPED, AND AFTER ASSESSING THE SCENE, SUMMONED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND THE LOCAL CUPA.  AFTER SEEING THE SITUATION WAS BEING APPROPRIATELY HANDLED, THE FD LEFT THE SCENE.  MATT LENTZ WITH THE CITY OF ANAHEIM ARRIVED TO OVERSEE CLEAN-UP ACTIVITIES.  THE LOCAL PD ASSUMED THE ROLE OF TRAFFIC CONTROL, TO MINIMIZE VEHICLES DRIVING THROUGH THE SPILLED MATERIALS, AND BLOCKING TRAFFIC FROM CLEAN-UP CREWS.  AT THE TIME OFFICE OF EMERGENCY SERVICES OES WAS CONTACTED REPORT #052346, AS WELL AS THE NRC, REPORT #756252, AS IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A REPORTABLE QUANTITY (RQ) HAS SPILLED ABOUT 186 GALLONS.  THE MATERIAL WAS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID WITH THE FOLLOWING SHIPPING DESCRIPTION:  PETROLEUM DISTILLATES N.O.S. 3, UN1268, PGII, RQ (XYLENE, NAPHTHALENE)  ADDITIONAL PERSONNEL ARRIVED AND AFTER ABSORBING THE LIQUIDS, THE AREA WAS PRESSURE WASHED.  THE CONTAMINATED USED ABSORBENT WITH DRUMMED FOR INCINERATION, AND THE RECOVERED SOLVENT/WATER MIXTURE WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE TANKER.  BY 3:30 PM ALL MATERIALS HAD BEEN CLEANED-UP TO THE SATISFACTION OF ANAHEIM POLICE OFFICER ROBERT MCKAY, AND THE INCIDENT WAS DECLARED OVER.

On April 25th, 2005 at 4:00 p.m. cdt a driver of a tanker operated by ADM Trucking, Inc. pulled over to an exit to inspect his load. While inspecting the load  he noticed the pump bleed off valve was open and approximately 5 gallons of sodium hydroxide was released onto the side of the roadway at I-55 263 mm. At approximately 4:01 pm CDT, Mr Al Carnahan with ADM Trucking retained Cura Emergency Services(CES) to manage the enviromental cleanup operation. Based onthe available information the CES incident manager dispatched a crew with Hazchem Eniviromental(CECS) to initiate corrective actions. The crew with Hazchem arrivedd and located the released material on the side of the roadway. Soduim bicarbonate was placed onto the release area and workers worked in with brooms. The spent sodium bicabonate waas collected and placed into a 55-gallon drum for disposal. No visual or olfactory evidence of sodium hydroxide was evident. the site was returned to prespill condition.
column169: Driver was retrained on the requirements of load securement of a cargo tank.

column168: Our driver pulled away from the loading site with the top bleed off valve open.  He noted something splashig off side of trailer.  He stopped while still on Sunoco property  and was observed on top of the trailer by Sunoco personnel, Steve Wybranski, Plant Protection.  He asked if there was a problem and our driver stated that he thought the liquid was water from the wash down at the rack, but in fact it was a small quantity of spent sulfuric acid coming out of the open Chicago fitting.  The driver closed the valve and returned to the loading rack and washed down the trailer into the rack's sump.  Sunoco personnel from Emergency Responce team applied soda ash on roadway to neutralize acid.
column169: Extensive retraining was done on May 4th and 5th with the driver in question as well as all drivers involved in the project at Marcus Hook by our safety director, Robert Mitchell.  A detailed and specific check list spelling out the duties necessary for the safe loading and unloading of sulfuric and spent sulfuric acid was developed and is now in place.

column168: Flight 1219/25APR, Ship 950 diverted to RIC at 1510 hours.  Flight control advised passenger Sally Mixon, Seat 22D was in possession of a liquid oxygen container.    Flight 1219 arrived at gate B-1 at 1510 hours and Station Manager Carla Sutera and Performance Leader Tim Manning met the flight.  After coordination with flight control, Carla Sutera briefed with the Captain/Co-Pilot and advised the passenger would be removed from the aircraft and the flight would depart ASAP.  The aircraft departed 21 minutes later at 1531.    Sally Mixon was traveling with her 11 year old son, Rashawn Mixon and both parties were removed from the flight.  Carla Sutera met with Ms. Mixon in the B-1 gatehouse.  AFSD/TSA Elizabeth Borreson arrived and spoke with the passenger as well.   FAA did not respond, but was in contact with Dangerous Goods Management Stephanie Horwitz. FAA Louis Fernandez called the RIC station at 0825, April 26th and advised he would be out at 1330 hours to obtain the contact information and view the unit.     Carla Sutera received a verbal statement from Ms. Mixon:  Ms. Mixon advised she has numerous medical problems and requires the oxygen on a limited basis when walking.  She had traveled from HSV-ATL-BDL on April 23, 2005 to attend a fund raiser in BDL.  The Oxygen Container was taken on the previous trip with no incident.  Upon departing BDL, Ms. Mixon did not advise anyone she was in possession of the Oxygen.  Ms. Mixon stated that while going through the checkpoint in BDL, they identified the oxygen container, checked it out and allowed her to transit the security checkpoint.      Ms. Mixon boarded the aircraft and before departure, the flight attendant identified the item, which was believed initially to be an oxygen concentrator, and advised her she would need to put it in the overhead bin.  Before departure the flight attendant came back to her and advised her she would need to hold the unit, which she did for takeoff.  Between pushback and takeoff, Ms. Mixon advised the cabin felt stuffy and she proceeded to use the unit on board the aircraft.  After takeoff, Ms. Mixon said the flight attendant came back with her manual and said the item was not allowed.  Shortly after this, the flight diverted.     Flight attendant initially believed the device was an oxygen concentrator.  Oxygen concentrators may be transported but not used during flight.  As soon as Flight attendant realized the unit was possibly a Liquid Oxygen device instead of an oxygen concentrator, the passenger was questioned.  After recieving confirmation of liquid oxygen, flight attendant contacted captain and diversion scenario was initiated.     The unit was a Puritan Bennett, Helios 300 portable liquid oxygen container which is 3/4 full. Photo's of the unit are attached.     Ms. Mixon was very gracious and polite during the interview and several times indicated she had traveled with this unit on previous trips and she had no idea the unit was not allowed.      Ms. Mixo

DURING AN ATTEMPTED AMMONIA THEFT, THE THIEF LEFT THE VALVE OPEN WHEN THEY WERE TRYING TO STEAL THE AMMONIA.  THE BOONE COUNTY SHERIFF DEPT. RECEIVED A CALL FROM A WOMAN AND DISPATCHED LIZTON FIRE DEPT. AND COUNTY SHERIFFS TO THE SCENE.  COUNTY SHERIFFS CONTACTED MAURICE CROUCH WHO IS A SALES REP. FROM ROYSTER-CLARK ROUGHLY AT 2:00 A.M.  MAURICE ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 2:15 A.M.  THE LIZTON F.D. SHUT OFF THE VALVE.  SOME OF THE GROUND IN FRONT OF THE NURSE TANK WITH THE OPEN VALVE WAS FROZEN.  THERE WAS A CLOUD THAT DRIFTED WEST OF THE AMMONIA SITE AND HOVERED ABOVE A FARMER'S FIELD.  IT FINALLY DISSIPATED IN THE ATMOSPHERE.  THE SHERIFF AND FIRE DEPT. CLOSED THE COUNTY ROAD FOR A TIME.  THERE WERE NO EVACUATIONS AND NO INJURIES.  THE AMOUNT RELEASED IS UNKNOWN.  AT 7:25 A.M., GREG GROVES, EHS ADMINISTRATOR WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.  GREG CALLED THE NRC, IDNR, BOONE COUNTY LEPC AND REPORTED THE RELEASE.  GREG MET BILL MYERS FROM IDEM AT THE SITE WITH MAURICE FROM LEBANON/NEW BRUNSWICK FARMARKET.  MR. MYERS REQUESTED THAT WE EXCAVATE THE SOIL THAT WAS FROZEN AND WANTED BOTH A BACKGROUND SAMPLE AND A SAMPLE OF THE FROZEN AREA AFTER THE EXCAVATION.  LAND APPLICATION OF THE SOIL WAS APPROVED.  HIGHLAND EXCAVATING EXVACATED THE CONTAMINATED SOIL AND THE SOIL WAS LAND APPLIED ON DICK HYSON'S FIELD BEHIND THE AMMONIA INSTALLATION.  CLEAN FILL DIRT AND GRAVEL WERE BROUGHT IN TO REPLACE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  SAMPLES WERE PULLED AND SENT TO A&L LABS ON 4/4/05.  RESULTS WILL BE SUBMITTED TO IDEM ALONG WITH A COPY OF THIS SPILL REPORT.

UNIT ONE THEN BEGAN TO ROTATE IN A COUNTER CLOCKWISE DIRECTION CROSSING THE NORTHBOUND LANES AND STRUCK THE GUARDRAIL ON THE RIGHT SHOULDER OF THE ROADWAY.  UNIT ONE WAS THEN FACING WESTBOUND IN THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF TRAVEL WHEN IT WAS STRUCK BY UNIT TWO.  THIS IS DETERMINED BY THE DAMAGE TO THE CRASH CUSHION/IMPACT ATTENUATOR WITH DEBRIS FROM UNIT ONE IN AND AROUND THE AREA, TIRE MARKINGS AND ROADWAY GOUGE MARKS FROM UNIT ONE ON THE ROADWAY AND PAINT TRANSFER FROM UNIT ONE ONTO THE GUARDRAIL.  UNIT TWO, A 2004 INTERNATIONAL 940 TRACTOR/TRAILER (SEMI) WHITE IN COLOR, DRIVE BY CHARLES D ROBINSON SR. OF PELZER, SC WAS NORTHBOUND ON I-0075 WHEN IT STRUCK UNIT ONE IN THE LEFT SIDE.  UNIT TWO THEN CONTINUED NORTHBOUND OVERTURNING, STRIKING THE GUARDRAIL AND CONTINUING OVER AN EARTH EMBANKMENT COMING TO REST IN AN AREA OF TREES.  UNIT TWO WAS ENGULFED IN FIRE AND WAS DESTROYED.  BOTH OCCUPANTS WERE FATALLY INJURED.

ON THE WAY TO THE FIELD ON BURNS ROAD, A REAR TIRE ON THE NURSE TANK BLEW, BREAKING THE HITCH AND CAUSING THE NURSE TANK TO GO INTO THE DITCH AND ROLL ON ITS SIDE.  AS A RESULT OF THE ROLL, THE POP-OFF AND VAPOR VALVES BROKE OFF THE TOP OF THE TANK.  LIQUID STAYED IN THE TANK AND PRODUCED A VAPOR ONLY FOR APPROX. 15-20 MINUTES UNTIL THE HOLES COULD BE PLUGGED.  THE TANK WAS UPRIGHTED AND LOADED ONTO A GOOSENECT TRAILER AND RETURNED TO ROYSTER-CLARK MILFORD CENTER.  THE VAPORS DRIFTED TOWARDS THE RESIDENCE OF SCOTT AND LORI REED AND KILLED THE FISH IN THEIR FOUNTAIN POND WHICH IS NEXT TO THE ROAD.  THEIR SON WAS CARRIED TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM AS A PRECAUTION TO HAVE HIM CHECKED FOR NH3 VAPORS.  HE CHECKED OUT OK AND WAS RELEASED.  THE VAPORS DISSIPATED ON THEIR OWN.
column169: ASSOCIATES AT THE ROYSTER-CLARK MILFORD CENTER, OH, FARMARKET WERE RETRAINED TO CAREFULLY INSPECT ALL NURSE TANKS, INCLUDING THE TIRES, BEFORE ALLOWING THEM TO BE PULLED OFF THE PREMISES.

column168: WHILE CHECKING THE SHIPMENT AN AA CARGO EMPLOYEE DISCOVERED A SMALL TUBE SHAPED OBJECT WITH "POISON" LABELING & MARKINGS.  THE CARGO ARRIVED FROM STI ONBOARD FLIGHT 738/05 APRIL.  THE PRODUCT WAS DETERMINED TO BE A CLASS 4.3 FLAMMABLE SOLID WITH A SUBSIDIARY RISK OF 6.1 TOXIC.  THE TUBE WAS FOUND INSIDE AN OUTERPACK BOX THAT WAS DECLARED AS "TOBACCO PRODUCTS - CIGARS".  THIS BOX WAS 1 OF 26 LOT.  ALL REMAINING BOXES OF THIS SHIPMENT WERE X-RAYED AND NO OTHER DG ITEMS WERE FOUND.  THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION AND RELEASED ON 04/08/05 BY THE FAA.  THE SEALED TUBE CONTAINED 30 ALUMINUM PHOSHIDE TABLETS UN1397.
column169: THIS SHIPMENT CONTAINED UNDECLARED HIDDEN DG ITEMS.  UPON DISCOVERY BY AA CARGO EMPLOYEES ALL REPORTING PROCEDURES WERE PROPERLY FOLLOWED.

column168: ON APRIL 12, 2005, TANKCAR GATX 7993 WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT FROM TOP OF CAR.  MR. JOHN JACKSON, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MR. JACKSON INSPECTED THE TANKCAR AND OBSERVED APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE LIQUID LINE CLOSURE CAP.  MR. JACKSON REMOVED THE LIQUID LINE CAP, RESEALED THE THREADS ON THE LIQUID LINE WITH SEALANT TAPE AND REPLACED THE CAP, TOOL TIGHT.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC.  SHIPPER CONTRACTED WITH VIVA ENVIRONMENTAL TO NEUTRALIZE AND CLEAN THE PRODUCT ON THE CAR AND REMEDIATE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WHERE APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS HAD REACHED THE GROUND UNDER THE CAR.  SHIPPER, REQUESTED UPRR RETURN THE TANKCAR TO THE ACID FACILITY AT WESTERN REFINERY FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.
column169: WESTERN REFINERY IS INSTALLING A PRESSURE LINE AT THE ACID FACILITY TO TEST THE CARS FOR LEAKAGE BEFORE THEY ARE OFFERED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

THE PRD O'RING WAS FOUND DETERIORATED, AND WAS REPLACED.  NO FURTHER LEAKS DETECTED.  THE SHIPPER WILL REQUEST A MOVEMENT AUTHORITY TO GATX FACILITY IN WAYCROSS, GA.

(NOTED: THE BLEACH WAS CONTAINED IN THE PLANT'S SEWER SYSTEM).  MS BURKETT GAVE PERMISSION TO RELEASE THE 20 GALLONS OF 12.5% BLEACH.  THE ROOT CAUSE WAS OPERATOR ERROR.  NOTE: NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED UNTIL GIVEN PERMISSION.  (20 GALLONS)  OUR PLANT IS SELF CONTAINED.

column168: THE PACKAGE ENTERED OUR FDC FACILITY AND WAS AUDITED BY LINA HUARTA.  LINA QUESTIONED THE INVOICE ENTRY "LIQUID FRAGRANCES SAMPLE."  THE PACKAGE WAS INSPECTED AND ISNIDE WAS DISCOVERED A 4 OZ GLASS BOTTLE MARKED "FLAVORED MOUTHWASH ALCOHOL."  WE CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND THEY FAXED US A MSDS.  THE MSDS INDICATED THAT THE BOTTLE CONTAINED "DENATURED ALCOHOL NA1987."  WE THEN CONTACTED HMSC AND MEGAN INSTRUCTED US TO HOLD THE PACKAGE FOR POSSIBLE FAA INSPECTION AND TO FILL OUT HM10 AND 5800.1 PAPERWORK.

ON APRIL 5, 2005, A TRACTOR-TRAILER OPERATED BY KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES (VERNON SAWYER) WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON I-10 WHEN THE DRIVER SWERVED TO AVOID HITTING AN OBJECT IN THE ROAD WAY.  THE DRIVER LOST CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND LANDED ON ITS SIDE.  AS A RESULT, THE ROOF OF THE TRAILER WAS BREACHED RELEASING ALL OF THE CARGO ON BOARD.  THE CARGO CONSISTED OF SEVERAL DRUMS OF MINERAL SPIRITS AND NON REGULATED/REGULATED PAINT.  THE DRUMS SUFFERED DAMAGE AS A RESULT OF THE VEHICLE ROLLOVER AND WERE OBSERVED LEAKING ONTO THE NEARBY ROAD SHOUDLER WHEN THE TRACTOR-TRAILER CAME TO A STOP.  AS ESTIMATED 3800 GALLONS OF SOLVENT AND PAINT WAS RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER.  THE IMPACT AREA DIMENSIONS MEASURED 250 FEET LONG BY 10 FEET WIDE.  APPROXIMATELY 150 SQUARE FEET WAS ALSO IMPACTED ON BOTH SIDES OF THE INTERSTATE SERVICE ROAD.  ON APRIL 5, 2005, CURA EMERGENCY SERVICES (CES) WAS CONTACTED BY KLLM TRANSPORT SERVICES TO MANAGE THE CLEAN UP OPERATIONS FOLLOWING THIS INCIDENT.  CES CONTACTED LOCAL AUTHORITIES ON SITE TO GAIN SUPPORTING INFORMATION.  BASED ON THE INFORMATION GIVEN, CES RETAINED A CREW FROM B&B FIRE AND SAFETY SERVICES (B&B) TO PERFORM A SITE ASSESSMENT AND PROCEED WITH CORRECTIVE ACTIONS ON SITE.  ON APRIL 5, 2005, A CREW FROM B&B MOBILIZED TO THE SITE AND BEGAN VACUUMING UP THE FREE PRODUCT FROM THE ROAD SHOULDER AND DEPLOYED ABSORBENT MATERIAL OVER THE RELEASE.  IN ADDITION, THE CREW COLLECTED THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS AND PALLETS FROM THE SITE AND PLACED THEM IN ROLL OFF BOXES FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE.  ON APRIL 6, 2005 B&B RETURNED TO THE SITE AND EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SOIL TO A DEPTH OF 5 FEET.  IMPACTED SOIL WAS PLACED IN ROLL OFF BOXES FOR DISPOSAL AT A LATER DATE.  THE EXCAVATION WAS BACKFILLED WITH CLEAN SOIL AND GRADED.

column168: ON 0830 HOUR ON APRIL 30TH TANK CAR GATX 53212 (LOAD - FLAMMABLE LIQUID, N.O.S.) WAS REPORTED BY A TRAIN CREW WORKING IN SPARTANBURG YARD WITH A SPLASH LEAK FROM TOP OF CAR.  CSX MANAGEMENT IMMDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATION'S TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  THE AREA AROUND THE RAIL CAR WAS ISOLATED.  THE SHIPPER, FLINT INK WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC (REPORT# 04302005027).  FLINT INK SENT OUT REPRESENTATIVES TO SECURE THE CONTAINER.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND THAT THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A DETERIORATED MANWAY GASKET.  APPROXIMATELY TWO (2) GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPLASHED ON THE SIDES OF THE RAIL CAR WHICH WAS ABSORBED BY PADS.  FLINT INK RESPONDERS REPLACED THE MANWAY GASKET AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

LOCAL MECHANICAL FORCES FOUND LTCX 1902, LOAD OF ARGON, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, CONTINUOUSLY VENTING PRODUCT TO ATMOSPHERE.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED, REPORT #04282005085.  PRAXAIR NOTIFIED CSX THAT THEY WOULD SEND A TECH REP OUT TO REPAIR LEAK.  THE SPRING LOCK TENSION SYSTEM ON THE VAPOR VALVE WAS NOT APPLIED PROPERLY AT SHIPPER, CAUSING VALVE TO FROST OVER.
column169: LOADING/UNLOADING PROCEDURES AT SHIPPER SHOULD BE REVIEWED.

column168: AT 1820 HOURS ON APRIL 22ND TANK CAR RCRX1096 WAS REPORTED BY A YARD TRAIN CREW RELEASING A "WHITE CLOUD" FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AT OUR CSX TRANSPORTATION'S AUGUSTA YARD.  CSX MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE CORPORATION'S TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  THE AREA AROUND THE RAIL CAR WAS ISOLATED.  THE SHIPPER, REAGENT CHEMICAL & RESEARCH WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC (REPORT #04222005099).  HEPACO ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CONTACTED TO RESPOND AND CONTAIN THE RELEASE.  UPON ARRIVAL HEPACO REPRESENTATIVES NOTED THAT ONE OF THE THREE FILL HOLE SECUREMENT BOLTS / NUTS WAS BROKEN.  THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO THE MISSING BOLT WHICH RESULTED IN THE IMPROPER SECUREMENT OF THE FILL HOLE COVER.  THE SWIVEL STYLE BOLT MEASURED 1" IN DIAMETER BY 6" IN LENGTH.  AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE, CONDUCTOR CLARENCE MIDDLETON AND TRAINMAN MITCHELL DINKINS REQUESTED MEDICAL ATTENTION.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED TO AUGUSTA'S UNIVERSITY HOSPITAL.  THEY WERE TREATED BY THE EMERGENCY ROOM PHYSICIAN, THE RELEASED WITH NO PRESCRIBED MEDICATIONS.  APPROXIMATELY THREE (3) GALLONS OF ACID WAS RELEASED FROM THE RAIL CAR.  THIS PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED WITH CHEMICAL PADS WHICH WERE THEN PLACED IN AN OVERPACK DRUM THAT IS CURRENTLY SCHEDULED FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL.  REAGENT CHEMICAL ARRANGED TO SHIP A NEW FILL HOLE SECUREMENT BOLT/ NUT TO HEPACO.  THE BOLT / NUT WAS INSTALLED ON TUESDAY, APRIL 26TH AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

ON 4/15/05 AT 12:50, TRAIN MASTER RAY CANADY OF ERWIN, TN., CALLED TO SAY THAT WHEN TANK CAR ETCX 421071 WAS MOVED, THERE WAS A SPLASH LEAK FROM THE MANWAY COVER ON TOP OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED IN TRACK E12.  EASTMAN CHEMICAL WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO THE INCIDENT.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND THAT ONE OF THE TWO LOCKING SWING BOLTS WAS BENT AND FERREL WAS CAUGHT UNDER THE LID PREVENTING THE MANWAY COVER FROM MAKING SEAL WITH THE GASKET EVEN THOUGH THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE ALL WRENCH TIGHT.  THEY ADJUSTED THE SWING BOLT PROPERLY AND SECURED THE MANWAY COVER.
column169: KELLY WILLIAMS, EASTMAN CHEMICAL LOGISTICS, STATED THAT THE 7 CARS IN THIS SERIES WOULD BE CLEANED, PURGED, AND THAT THE SWING BOLTS WOULD BE REPLACED ON THE CARS AT EASTMAN CHEMICAL.

SAM KEPHART, DIRECTOR OF TERMINAL OPERATIONS, REPORTED LOADED TANKCAR GATX 80509 WAS VENTING FROM THE SEAL ON THE TOP OF THE CAR WITH NO PRODUCT REACHING THE GROUND AND NO INJURIES.  ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 09:00 PM, BAVIER ADVISED THE TANKCAR LEAKAGE HAD STOPPED AND ALL THE PRODUCT HAD EVAPORATED.  MR. BAVIER FURTHER STATED THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS A LOOSE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE AND REPAIRS WOULD BE INITIATED.
column169: SECURE THE TANKCAR BEFORE LEAVING THE PLANT.

column168: BRIAN BEAZER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD WAS NOTIFIED OF AN EMPLOYEE BEING SPRAYED WITH SULFURIC ACID FROM RAILROAD TANKCAR FXE 418078 ON TRACK 4 IN THE TUCSON, AZ TRAIN YARD.  MR. BEAZER ARRIVED AT THE REPORTED LOCATION AND INSPECTED THE TANK CAR IN QUESTION AND OBSERVED MOISTURE AROUND THE BASE OF THE FILL HOLE, AND DROPLETS OF PRODUCT ON THE CATWALK.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE FILL HOLE COVER GASKET WAS DEFECTIVE.  THE GASKET MATERIAL WAS FOUND TO BE HARD AND WOULD NOT SEAL PROPERLY WHEN THE FILL HOLE COVER LID WAS SECURED.  ALL SECURING BOLTS TO THE LID WERE FOUND TO BE PROPERLY SECURED WRENCH TIGHT.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED, AND REPLACED THE GASKET IN QUESTION, AND PROPERLY SECURED THE FILL HOLE COVER LID, WITH NO OTHER EXCEPTIONS NOTED.
column169: SHIPPER TO RE-ADDRESS QUALITY CONTROL MEASURES WHEN LOADING AND SECURING SULFURIC ACID TANK CARS.
